    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is emotional intelligence?</summary>
        <p>Emotional intelligence (EQ or EI) is the ability to recognize, understand, manage, and effectively use emotions in yourself and in your interactions with others. The concept was popularized by psychologist Daniel Goleman and includes four core domains: Self-Awareness, Self-Management, Social Awareness, and Relationship Management. Unlike IQ, which is relatively fixed, EQ can be developed and strengthened at any age through deliberate practice. <a href="/test/emotional-intelligence-test/">Take our free Emotional Intelligence Test</a> to assess your current EQ.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can EQ be improved?</summary>
        <p>Yes, emotional intelligence can absolutely be improved at any age. Because EQ is a set of skills rather than a fixed trait, it responds to deliberate practice and learning. Research in neuroplasticity shows that the brain regions involved in emotional processing and regulation can be strengthened through consistent practice. Effective strategies include mindfulness meditation, emotional journaling, active listening exercises, seeking feedback from trusted others, and working with a therapist or coach. Most people see measurable improvement within a few months of consistent practice.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is EQ more important than IQ?</summary>
        <p>Research suggests that EQ is a stronger predictor of success in many life domains than IQ alone. Studies have found that EQ accounts for roughly 58 percent of performance across all job types, and 90 percent of top performers have high emotional intelligence. However, IQ and EQ are not in competition. They measure different capabilities that complement each other. IQ tends to matter more for technical problem-solving, while EQ matters more for leadership, teamwork, communication, and navigating complex interpersonal situations. The most successful people tend to leverage both.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is EQ measured?</summary>
        <p>EQ is measured through several validated assessment tools, each taking a different approach. The Mayer-Salovey-Caruso Emotional Intelligence Test (MSCEIT) uses ability-based tasks where you solve emotional problems. The Emotional Quotient Inventory (EQ-i 2.0) uses self-report questions about your typical behavior. There are also 360-degree assessments that incorporate feedback from peers, managers, and direct reports. No single test captures the full picture, and a combination of self-assessment and external feedback provides the most accurate view of your EQ.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are signs of high emotional intelligence?</summary>
        <p>Signs of high emotional intelligence include the ability to identify and name your emotions accurately, staying calm and composed under pressure, being genuinely curious about other people's experiences, adapting your communication style to different audiences, taking responsibility for mistakes without excessive self-blame, handling criticism without becoming defensive, resolving conflicts in ways that preserve relationships, and maintaining strong connections across different areas of your life. People with high EQ are often described by others as empathetic, composed, approachable, and easy to work with.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

